<h2 id="post-93"><a href="http://dirk-kutscher.info/publications/ietf/requirements-for-accessing-data-in-network-storage/" rel="bookmark">Requirements for accessing data in network storage</a></h2>
<p class="comments"><a href="http://dirk-kutscher.info/publications/ietf/requirements-for-accessing-data-in-network-storage/#comments">without comments</a></p>

<div class="main">
	<p>Internet Draft on requirements for accessing data in network storage (Requirements for accessing data in network storage).</p>
<p><strong>Abstract:</strong></p>
<blockquote><p>
The DECoupled Application Data Enroute (DECADE) working group is<br />
   specifying standardized interfaces for accessing in-network storage<br />
   from applications to store, retrieve and manage data.  The main<br />
   objective is to provide a framework that is useful to P2P<br />
   applications, without excluding other, possibly related applications<br />
   that can benefit from accessing in-network storage.  This memo<br />
   presents Internet TV as a specific application scenario where access<br />
   to in-netork storage would be required and lists a set of concrete<br />
   requirements that should be considered for the DECADE architecture<br />
   and protocol specifications.
</p></blockquote>
<p><a href="http://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ohlman-decade-add-use-cases-reqs/">draft-ohlman-decade-add-use-cases-reqs-02</a></p>
</div>

<div class="meta group">
<div class="signature">
    <p>Written by dkutscher <span class="edit"></span></p>
    <p>Februar 12th, 2011 at 6:33 pm</p>
